<subSubSection id="C35665184C08675AFF642B2A8707EEBB" pageId="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF336934C08675AFF642B2A8707EEBB" blockId="24.[151,639,194,1730]" pageId="24">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFF642B2A846EED4F" bold="true" box="[175,279,300,321]" pageId="24">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This group of flightless blapstinoid species are characterized by the anterior fusion of the seventh and eighth striae that do not reach the base of the elytron (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE942B7A84D1ED9F" box="[351,424,380,401]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
); a smooth-bottomed, delimited groove on ventrite I immediately bordering the metacoxa (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFEA22BB784D6EDC8" box="[361,431,433,454]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
) (one exception); the aedeagus with the basal piece strongly arched and the parameres weakly sinuate in lateral view, the parameres at least slightly widened from the base to midpoint, then obliquely tapered to the rounded tip (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFF0B2830846AEE45" box="[192,275,566,587]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Figs. 39</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D104C08675AFEEC28308486EE45" box="[295,511,566,587]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Xerolinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="waterhousei">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFEEC28308486EE45" box="[295,511,566,587]" italics="true" pageId="24">Xerolinus waterhousei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an exception, as it has a line of punctures behind the metacoxa, but has the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D104C08675AFE90286D84CFEE8E" authorityName="Ivie and Hart" authorityYear="2016" box="[347,438,619,640]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Xerolinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFE90286D84CFEE8E" box="[347,438,619,640]" italics="true" pageId="24">Xerolinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="54F788314C08675AFE0F286D8494EE8E" box="[452,493,619,640]" pageId="24">type</typeStatus>
of striae and aedeagus. This large and diverse group requires further study, several undescribed species are known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35665184C08675AFF6428BC86F4EDEF" pageId="24" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF336934C08675AFF6428BC86F4EDEF" blockId="24.[151,639,194,1730]" lastBlockId="24.[685,1172,194,932]" pageId="24">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFF6428BC8453EEC1" bold="true" box="[175,298,698,719]" pageId="24">Description.</emphasis>
Length: 4.5–11.0 mm. Body oval to elongate oval (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE8728D384E1EEE4" box="[332,408,725,746]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
), convex above; black except apical antenomeres, palps, setae, and tarsal pads variable, often reddish to golden or whitish. Head transverse; variously punctate; epistoma margin emarginate; labrum visible, apically bearing 2 tufts of golden setae (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE0F295C8768EF61" box="[452,529,858,879]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) [must be clean to see this]; antennae with 11 antennomeres, weakly clavate (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFEF0298984FFEFAA" box="[315,390,911,932]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
); eyes small, divided by genal canthus, lobes subequal or lower somewhat smaller (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFF3829C28402EFD7" box="[243,379,964,985]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Figs. 37, 40</figureCitation>
); gula with anterolateral angles weakly to moderately produced (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFDEC29D9870AEFFA" box="[551,627,991,1012]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Pronotum matte, disc usually finely punctate; usually widest at base, occasionally widest anterior to base; anterior margin emarginate; posterior margin bisinuate, width at base subequal to humeral width; margins beaded (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE4E2E6284B6E877" box="[389,463,1124,1145]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
); hypomeron variably punctate to rugose; prosternal process acute, tip weakly displaced ventrally (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE0E2E9F8774E8A0" box="[453,525,1177,1198]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Scutellum variable, typically wider than long, triangular to rounded behind. Elytra fused together, locked to metathorax at epimeron; humeral angles narrowed; striae variable, from nearly totally effaced to deeply impressed and strongly punctate; striae 6 and 9 approaching at base, keeping striae 7 and 8 from reaching base (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE562F55849CE966" box="[413,485,1363,1384]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), 7 and 8 fused or approaching, not reaching base of elytron, not deflected towards lateral margin (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE292F8E8755E993" box="[482,556,1416,1437]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Mesoventrite short, deeply impressed to receive prosternal process (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFE8C2FBB84E0E9DC" box="[327,409,1469,1490]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Metathoracic wings extremely reduced or absent. Metaventrite short, equal to or less than 2/3, usually less than 1/2 length of mesocoxa; variably punctate. Legs variably punctate and setose, femora clavate (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFDE12C21870BEA32" box="[554,626,1575,1596]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
); femora unarmed; tibiae weakly expanded from base to apex, usually unarmed, occasionally with weak tooth on inner margin; males with protarsus and sometimes mesotarsus with tarsomeres 1–3 expanded, densely setose beneath (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFDED2CAA870AEACF" box="[550,627,1708,1729]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Abdominal ventrites variably punctate, from smooth and shining to rugose; ventrites 1–3 flattened or concave medially in male (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFC662AF1868AED02" box="[941,1011,247,268]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
), weakly convex in female; ventrite 1 usually with distinct, smoothbottomed grove adjacent to hind margin of metacoxa (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFD222B418649ED52" box="[745,816,327,348]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
), rarely with row of large punctures in this position. Aedeagus strongly curved in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFD212B7A8648ED9F" box="[746,817,380,401]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
), parameres weakly sinuate in lateral view; in dorsal view, parameres weakly broadened from base to midpoint, then tapered to a narrowly rounded apex (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFCF02BCA86F8EDEF" box="[827,897,460,481]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[197,236,1353,1372]" captionTargetBox="[183,1186,196,1319]" captionTargetId="figure-146@15.[173,1193,183,1330]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 37–42. Xerolinus sallei: 37) Dorsal habitus; 38) Humeral angle; 39) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 40) Head and thorax, ventral view; 41) Abdominal ventrites; 42) Aedeagus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496156/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35665184C08675AFD0E2BE08158EF34" pageId="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF336934C08675AFD0E2BE08158EF34" blockId="24.[685,1172,194,932]" pageId="24">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFD0E2BE0863FEDF5" bold="true" box="[709,838,486,507]" pageId="24">Distribution.</emphasis>
The 29 described species of recognized 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D104C08675AFD36280786D9EE18" box="[765,928,513,534]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Xerolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFD362807862FEE18" box="[765,854,513,534]" italics="true" pageId="24">Xerolinus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
occur from South Florida through the Lucayan Archipleago and Greater Antilles (
<figureCitation id="13772A164C08675AFCC22830862DEE45" box="[777,852,566,587]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[709,740,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[685,1171,1316,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-567@22.[685,1171,1316,1663]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 53. Distribution of the West Indian and south Caribbean blapstinoids." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496162" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496162/files/figure.png" pageId="24">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
), with one species reaching the 
<collectingCountry id="F35B76034C08675AFD66285686FBEE6B" box="[685,898,592,613]" name="British Virgin Islands" pageId="24">British Virgin Islands</collectingCountry>
. For the most part, they are single island or bank endemics. The center for the described members of the genus is the Cuban archipelago, with 19 described species, but the largely unstudied Lucayan Archipelago will almost certainly exceed that. Many species remain undescribed, including species from 
<collectingCountry id="F35B76034C08675AFBCC28F681F6EF0B" box="[1031,1167,752,773]" name="Bahamas" pageId="24">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F35B76034C08675AFD66290C8782EF11" box="[685,763,778,799]" name="Jamaica" pageId="24">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F35B76034C08675AFCC7290C86FCEF11" box="[780,901,778,799]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="24">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, and Great Camanoe, and many more islands remain unsampled.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35665184C08675AFD0E29468692EFAA" pageId="24" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF336934C08675AFD0E29468692EFAA" blockId="24.[685,1172,194,932]" pageId="24">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFD0E2946864EEF5B" bold="true" box="[709,823,832,853]" pageId="24">Etymology.</emphasis>
The prefix 
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFC7E29468692EF5B" box="[949,1003,832,853]" italics="true" pageId="24">Xeros</emphasis>
, from the Greek ξηρóς, meaning dry or arid, added to the suffix - 
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFD66297387A2EF84" box="[685,731,885,906]" italics="true" pageId="24">linus</emphasis>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D104C08675AFCD3297386FCEF84" authorityName="Mulsant and Rey, with a" authorityYear="1859" box="[792,901,885,906]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Diastolinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B938EA814C08675AFCD3297386FCEF84" box="[792,901,885,906]" italics="true" pageId="24">Diastolinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, referring to the xeric habitat characteristic of these beetles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
